## Platform-First Development -- READ THIS FIRST

Before building anything, **read the platform's documentation and search for existing solutions.** The vast majority of anti-patterns in this codebase came from reimplementing things the platform SDK already provides (Slack's `chatStream` vs manual message polling, E2B's per-command `envs` vs `.bashrc` hacks, Claude Code vs custom agent runner scripts).

**The workflow for any new feature or integration:**

1. **Read the SDK/library docs** for the platform you're integrating with. Check the `@docs` references in Cursor (e.g. `@Slack API`, `@AI-SDK`, `@E2B`). If the docs aren't indexed, fetch the relevant pages with WebFetch first.
2. **Search GitHub for real-world examples** — look at how other projects use the same SDK. Prefer official examples from the SDK vendor (e.g. `github.com/e2b-dev/e2b-cookbook`, `github.com/vercel/ai/examples`, `github.com/slackapi/bolt-js/examples`).
3. **Only build what's missing.** If the platform provides a feature (streaming, rate limiting, env injection, formatting), use it. Don't wrap it, don't rebuild it, don't "enhance" it with custom infrastructure.
4. **When you do build**, follow the patterns from official examples. Don't invent new patterns when the vendor has documented ones.

**Specific platform notes:**
- **Slack Web API (`@slack/web-api`)**: Use `chatStream` for streaming responses (not `postMessage` + `chat.update` polling). The SDK handles rate-limit retries internally — don't build a custom rate limiter. Use `markdown_text` in stream appends — Slack handles formatting.
- **E2B Sandboxes**: Always pass `envs` per-command via `commands.run(cmd, { envs })`. Don't rely on env vars persisting across pause/resume cycles. Use `getSandboxEnvs()` from `apps/api/src/lib/sandbox.ts`.
- **AI SDK v6**: Uses `inputSchema` (not `parameters`), `stopWhen: stepCountIs(N)` (not `maxSteps`). Check `https://v6.ai-sdk.dev/llms.txt` for the full API reference.
- **Vercel**: Serverless = stateless. In-memory caches only last one request. Don't build TTL/expiry logic for caches that die with the process.

**Red flags that you're about to over-engineer:**
- Writing more than ~20 lines to wrap a single SDK call
- Adding a new dependency to solve a problem the existing SDK already handles
- Building a "fallback" for something you haven't verified is broken
- Creating a rigid tool when a general primitive + knowledge (skill/rule) would work

## Deployment

- **NEVER push directly to `main`.** Vercel auto-deploys from `main`, so any push goes straight to production. Always create a feature branch, push it, and open a PR. Merging the PR triggers the deploy.
- **Use `npx --yes vercel@50.13.2` for CLI operations** (the project doesn't have Vercel CLI installed globally). Always use `--scope realadvisor`.
- **Migrations run automatically** during API build (`tsc && pnpm --filter @aura/db db:migrate`).
- **Production URL**: `https://aura-alpha-five.vercel.app`

## Database

- **Schema**: `packages/db/src/schema.ts` — single source of truth
- **Migrations**: `packages/db/drizzle/` — generated by `pnpm db:generate`
- **Apply migrations**: `pnpm db:migrate` (runs automatically on deploy)
- **Drizzle config**: `packages/db/drizzle.config.ts`
- Both apps depend on `@aura/db` (workspace link) — import via `@aura/db/schema`

## Environment Variables

- **Add env vars via CLI**: `printf '%s' 'value' | npx --yes vercel@50.13.2 env add VAR_NAME production --scope realadvisor`
- **Always use `printf '%s'`** to pipe values -- never `echo` (it adds trailing newlines that break Vercel).
- **After adding env vars**, trigger a redeploy: either push a commit or run `npx --yes vercel@50.13.2 --prod --scope realadvisor`.
- **List env vars**: `npx --yes vercel@50.13.2 env ls --scope realadvisor`

## Vercel Logs

- **Stream runtime logs**: `npx --yes vercel@50.13.2 logs aura-alpha-five.vercel.app --scope realadvisor`
- Logs stream in real-time. Run in background with a timeout to capture output.
- Build logs are separate: `npx --yes vercel@50.13.2 inspect <deployment-url> --logs --scope realadvisor`

## Slack App

- **Slack app name**: Nova
- **Bot token env var**: `SLACK_BOT_TOKEN` (xoxb-...)
- **User token env var**: `SLACK_USER_TOKEN` (xoxp-...) -- for message search
- **Admin user IDs**: `AURA_ADMIN_USER_IDS` (comma-separated)
- When adding new Slack API methods, check if new bot scopes are needed and document them in the README.
- After adding scopes, the app must be reinstalled to the workspace.

## Coding Patterns

- **Tools**: Use AI SDK `tool()` with `inputSchema` (Zod) and `execute`. Group in `apps/api/src/tools/`.
- **Cron jobs**: Hono sub-apps in `apps/api/src/cron/`, entry points in `apps/api/api/cron/`, schedule in `apps/api/vercel.json`.
- **Caching**: Channel and user lists are cached per invocation to avoid redundant API calls.
- **Models**: Resolve dynamically via `getMainModel()` / `getFastModel()` / `getEmbeddingModel()` (DB first, then env var, then default).
- **System prompt**: Personality and cross-cutting behavioral rules in `apps/api/src/personality/system-prompt.ts`.

## Tool documentation convention

- Tool `description` fields are the **primary source** of "when/how to use" guidance for the LLM.
- The system prompt contains only **cross-cutting behavioral rules** (e.g. DM privacy, channel access), NOT per-tool documentation.
- When adding a new tool, put all usage guidance in the tool's `description` field, not the system prompt.

## Adding Dependencies -- CRITICAL

- **Use pnpm**: `pnpm --filter <app-name> add <package>` to add deps to a specific app.
- **NEVER use static `import` for optional/external SDKs** (e2b, tavily, etc.). Always use `await import("package")` inside the function that needs it. Static imports cause the module to load on EVERY request, and ESM-only packages (like those using `chalk`) will crash Vercel's CJS runtime.
- **After adding any new npm package**, verify it works at runtime, not just type-checking. `tsc --noEmit` does NOT catch ESM/CJS compatibility issues.
- **Check if the package is ESM-only** before adding it. If it is, it MUST be dynamically imported.
- **Pattern for optional dependencies**:
  ```typescript
  // GOOD: dynamic import, loads only when needed
  async function doThing() {
    const { SomeSDK } = await import("some-sdk");
    return SomeSDK.create();
  }
  
  // BAD: static import, loads on every cold start, crashes if ESM-only
  import { SomeSDK } from "some-sdk";
  ```

## GitHub Access

- `GITHUB_TOKEN` is a PAT scoped to `realadvisor/aura` (contents + PRs)
- Passed to E2B sandbox via `envs` for git/gh CLI operations
- Aura can read her own code via `read_own_source` tool (GitHub API, no sandbox needed)
- **NEVER push to `main`** -- always create a feature branch and open a PR (see Deployment section)
- For self-edits to `system-prompt.ts`, flag as "self-edit" in the PR

## TypeScript

- Always run `npx tsc --noEmit` before committing (in the relevant app directory).
- Use `.js` extensions in imports (ESM with `"type": "module"`).
- AI SDK v6 uses `inputSchema` (not `parameters`) and `stopWhen: stepCountIs(N)` (not `maxSteps`).
- Remember: `tsc` catches type errors but NOT runtime issues (ESM/CJS, missing env vars, API incompatibilities). Be extra careful with new dependencies.
